{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CdH7v2YgUXDKifK97Qz9q","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Tests pass.\n\n## What was wrong\n\n`getUsers` cached results under a key of only `opts.team`:\n\n```js\nconst key = `users:${opts.team}`;\n```\n\nBut the result depends on `includeArchived` too. When any caller requested `getUsers({ team, includeArchived: true })`, the archived-inclusive result got stored under `users:<team>`. The people picker's own `getUsers({ team, includeArchived: false })` call then read that same cache entry and showed archived users it never asked for. The 60s TTL is exactly why refreshing after a minute clears it — the poisoned entry expires.\n\n## The fix\n\nInclude `includeArchived` in the cache key so the two request shapes get distinct entries:\n\n```js\nconst key = `users:${opts.team}:${opts.includeArchived ? \"all\" : \"active\"}`;\n```\n\nNote the existing test suite (`test/cache.test.js`) only covers the cache primitive — there's no test exercising `getUsers` cache-key isolation. Worth adding one if you want a regression guard against this class of bug; let me know and I'll write it."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":316,"cache_read_input_tokens":22805,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":316},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"36b86266-be9d-401a-9e61-c27f0019a344","uuid":"226c517a-ebfe-4b8e-b8f3-f2f68c6604f1","timestamp":"2026-07-22T12:46:46.179Z","request_id":"req_011CdH7uz4MwXJntRBiKmdPe"}
